  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes with
an assertion failure in VPTransformState::get when trying to obtain a value for
a non-first lane of a VPValue produced by a VPExpandSCEVRecipe. The assertion
hasVectorValue(Def) triggers because the value is neither available as a
per-lane scalar beyond lane 0 nor as a vector broadcast, and it is not
recognized as uniform-after-vectorization, so the code falls through to
requiring a vector value.\n\nThe problematic VPValue is the SCEV expansion of
the loop-invariant step \"(-65534 + %fr)\". In the generated VPlan this SCEV is
expanded in the entry block, producing a scalar value. During scalarization of
the replicated add instruction (%iv.next = add %iv, %step), the second operand
uses this SCEV value with Lane=1. Because it is scalar and loop-invariant, the
correct behavior is to use the lane-0 scalar for all lanes (uniform). However,
vputils::isUniformAfterVectorization currently does not recognize
VPExpandSCEVRecipe values as uniform, causing State.get to demand a vector value
and assert.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The VPlan shows EMIT vp<%1> = EXPAND
SCEV (-65534 + %fr)<nsw> in the entry block and the replicated region uses
VPScalarIVSteps with step vp<%1>.\n- The vectorizer decides to scalarize the
add/gep/store and indicates that the comparison is uniform, but for the
scalarized add, it still requests the operand vp<%1> at Lane>0.\n- State dump
confirms only lane 0 scalar exists for VPValue 0x55555560a810 (the
VPExpandSCEVRecipe result), no vector value stored.\n- The crash happens in
VPTransformState::get(Def, Lane) with Lane != 0 for that VPValue.\n\n3. Root
Cause Analysis:\n- VPExpandSCEVRecipe executes and sets a single scalar result
(lane 0) because the SCEV is loop-invariant. The infrastructure relies on
isUniformAfterVectorization(Def) to decide that higher-lane requests can reuse
the lane-0 scalar.\n- vputils::isUniformAfterVectorization lacks a case for
VPExpandSCEVRecipe, so it returns false unless the value is defined outside loop
regions; in this scenario the predicate evaluates to false and the code path
expects a vector value, which isn't set, leading to the assertion.\n- Therefore,
the uniformity analysis is incomplete: expanded SCEVs that are used as
loop-invariant scalars must be treated as uniform after vectorization.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanUtils.h, in
isUniformAfterVectorization(const VPValue *VPV)\n- Change: Recognize
VPExpandSCEVRecipe results as uniform after vectorization. Place this before the
default false case.\n\nConcrete patch idea (context around lines
~39-53):\ninline bool isUniformAfterVectorization(const VPValue *VPV) {\n  if
(VPV->isDefinedOutsideLoopRegions())\n    return true;\n  const VPRecipeBase
*Def = VPV->getDefiningRecipe();\n  assert(Def && \"Must have definition for
value defined inside vector region\");\n  // NEW: SCEV expansions are scalar
expansions and do not vary per lane.\n  if (isa<VPExpandSCEVRecipe>(Def))\n
return true;\n  if (auto *Rep = dyn_cast<VPReplicateRecipe>(Def))\n    return
Rep->isUniform();\n  if (auto *GEP = dyn_cast<VPWidenGEPRecipe>(Def))\n
return all_of(GEP->operands(), isUniformAfterVectorization);\n  if (auto *VPI =
dyn_cast<VPInstruction>(Def))\n    return VPI->isSingleScalar() ||
VPI->isVectorToScalar();\n  return false;\n}\n\nRationale:\n- VPExpandSCEVRecipe
expands SCEV into a scalar IR value, and in the VPlan it is placed in a block
outside the loop region or otherwise independent of lane. Treating it as uniform
ensures State.get will reuse the lane-0 scalar for lanes > 0, avoiding the
erroneous requirement for a vector value.\n- This aligns with how other
loop-invariant constructs are treated and matches VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute
expecting Step from lane 0.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy teaching
vputils::isUniformAfterVectorization that VPExpandSCEVRecipe results are
uniform, State.get(Def, Lane>0) will correctly return the lane-0 scalar, and the
assert will no longer trigger. This fixes the crash for the provided reproducer
and preserves intended semantics for loop-invariant SCEV expansions used in
scalarized operations across lanes.",
